text: imagine a country so small that offers such an abundance of landscape, architectural and cultural richness that a lifetime is not enough for you to see it all, so diverse from each other and unique with their personal taste and personality. In this video you have seen just some of them. Now think that Italy has been at the center of the Mediterranean, fusing the cultures of two different continents for thousands of years, as a welcome door or a goodbye one. Italy experiences long dominating phases (i.e. roman empire) or being dominated several times in history from many others, always giving to the other culture, keeping or leaving something to everyone, for hundreds of years doctors, artists and travelers came to Italy for their trip of a lifetime.. Italy has it all, a fantastic climate, warm people, wealth, art, creative abilities, a high-level industry that projects itself to be a power in the world, up und down but always there during the history. Italians have extraordinary taste and ability that often attract envy but also love and curiosity from all over the world. Italy has been a cultural center and will be so for a long time. and all this without mentioning for a moment its gastronomy, which everyone loves and is considered the best and richest in the world.

Limone sul Garda is a town in the province of Brescia, in Lombardy (northern Italy), at the western bank of Lake Garda, which is the largest Lake in Italy. text:
Hi Ryan Shirley. 

Please visit Lindesnes, the southern most tip of Norway.  you will find the oldest and southern most lighthouse in Norway. Lidenses  has a fantastic view of North sea. They say that in a clear day, you might see all the way to Denmark. However, i dont know if that is true. Lindesnes has many man made tunels made by the germans as watch points during the second world war. They wanted to see if Brittish military boats were comming to invade. It also has a cinema build in the rock, and walking path all around the area. Spangreid near by has a sea food restaurant build into the sea, and there is a canal there also for smaller boats, so they dont need to come arount the lindesnes tip with all its winds and big waves. 

The Northern most point of norway is Nordkap, that has a beatiful view og the sea, barentshavet,  and also has a cinema building. To travel in the north it is popular to take the boat, Hurtigruta, that is impotant for people in the north. It stops many places, and is important communication  sourse in the North. 

Kristiansand in the south has the biggest zoo in Norway, with animals from all over the world. and beatiful beaches and swimmingpools in the city center.

Bergen in the west has the biggest Aquarium, and it has the famus bryggen, with colourful old buildings. 

Oslo in the east is the capitol, and biggest city. Oslo has the biggest amusment park called tusenfryd in Norway. Oslo has a famous park, called Vigelandsparken. Its made of stone statues of naked people in all stages of life.  Also a ski jump called Holmenkollen, and a new Opera house made of marbel from Italy.  Marka , the woods around Oslo, is popular for people in the captitol to hike og skii, and aslo bygd√∏y is popular during the summer for museums and swimming. 

Toms√∏ in the north is know for its cathedral, Ishavskatedralen. You can see the northern lights and midnight sun there. 

Trondheim has the biggest Church, called Nidarosdomen, that holds the crown jewles of Norway. Christianity, fist catholic, then protestant, is important in Norway, and it also has a cross in its flag. 

You make great videows. Welcome back to Norway. I love to watch your travel guides on the youtube.

Is is typical when visiting Puglia to stay in a ‚ÄúTrullo‚Äù or a masseria, which are rural houses or farms converted into hotels, and many have pools as well; for that, the best area is the Itria Valley, which is basically between Bari and Salento. When in Puglia, it‚Äôs definitely worth visiting the city of Matera (in the near region of Basilicata), a very unique place where many movies where filmed (i.e. ‚ÄúThe passion of Christ‚Äù, ‚ÄúJames Bond‚Äù), and where it‚Äôs possible to sleep in traditional caves. Lastly, there is the Gargano (about 2 and half hours North Bari), an area of Puglia with other very beautiful villages and beaches that deserves a holiday on its own; the highlights are Vieste, Peschici, Monte Sant‚ÄôAngelo, and the Tremiti Islands. In comparison to other areas of Puglia, the Gargano has a more scenic and mountainous landscape, whereas Salento it‚Äôs mostly flat, but has the typical Mediterranean crystal clear water. text: ¬†@RyanShirley¬† Aloha Ryan,   Thanks for writing.   It's difficult to decide, but Tokyo is epic, made up of 23 wards.  Get to know them one by one.  I stayed in Shinjuko which has the tallest buildings in Tokyo, the red light district (which seemed mild) and an entertainment district with tons of restaurants and bars and arcades.  If you ever saw Godzilla on the roof of a building in a Tokyo pic, that is Shinjuko and was right next door to my hotel.  Roppongi is another popular Tokyo ward for nightlife.  Viator has lots of video clips of tour bus excursions to popular outlying areas from Tokyo , such as Mt. Fuji, with bullet train returns.  Flights are much cheaper into Osaka than into Tokyo, which can influence a decision.  Kobe is close to Osaka and built on a mountain and has an inland sea port.  I preferred Kobe to Osaka.  What is really special about an hour outside of Osaka is Kyoto, which was the capitol of Japan for over 1000 years.  Kyoto is loaded with historical sites. Gion in Kyoto is where Geisha originated.  Across the river from Gion is Ponto-cho, a food alley,, with classy restaurants with 20' high elevated outdoor patios above the walking trail along the river, loved that. Up north where it snows is Sapporo which has great restaurants in a much smaller urban setting.  400 miles south of mainland Japan is the island Okinawa, which was  supposed to see on the 4th trip.  Its a lot like Hawaii, where I live, but want to see it in my quest to be  an expert on the amazing  country of Japan.  Okinawa has many surrounding little islands too served by ferry boats offering world class snorkeling.  A friend who has a Japanese wife once told me Japan is like Hawaii in the south and Alaska in the north, that insight motivated me to book my first trip.  That, beer,, and sushi.  Mahalo,  Phil   P.S. Find tons of Japan videos from film makers not nearly as talented as you - right here on youtube!

text: ¬†@RyanShirley¬† For starters Ryan, there is a great youtube video from "Matt's Travel Tips" and his Tokyo video is titled :"8 Tips for an Awesome trip to Tokyo"  This 10 minute video is well done and funny - check it out.   It seems that COVID-19 is bad in Japan presently and for April there are decent $30 private rooms in Tokyo and $18 rooms in Okinawa today on expedia.  Typically the  rates are much higher. One thing to be aware of in Japan,  many hotels will charge rates per person vs. per room.   Also, there is no tipping; so in theory your food and beverage budget is bolstered up 20%.  Various mini-marts sell decent cooked food.  Family Marts have amazing fresh and delicious sushi bento boxes, nice to keep some on hand in the hotel fridge.  7-11's have the best morning coffee.  McDonald's have mastered perfection.  The Japanese are very nice and spiritual people.   They are smart and artistic.  They rely on God.  They are very hard workers and often its difficult to get time off work for vacationing.  Soaking in hot tubs is very common.  Many Japanese citizens live without a car as the public transportation is so good.  Have you ever seen a hotel laundry room, where one machine will wash, dry, provide the laundry soap, allow you to create a password to keep the lid locked until you return, and let you monitor its status from the big screen tv in your room several floors away?  KIX is Kansai International Airport, the newer one of two airports in Osaka.   Due to noise and urban land shortages, KIX was built on a man made island 4 miles out on the inland sea!  Before the pandemic, AirAsia routinely had $430 round trip tickets Honolulu to Osaka.  One per day in each direction.  3pm departures out of Honolulu, 11pm flights out of Osaka.  Living on Maui, its wonderful to book end Japan trips with a few nights in Waikiki or the North Shore on each end to break up  the flights.  Oh I miss travelling!
author: @philjorgensen1950

text: And one final point that was an issue for me in several cities in Japan:    The power supply cord for your notebook computer probably has 3-plugs and the majority of Japan has standardized on 2-plugs.  On my first trip in a Tokyo hi-rise, the room was all 2 plug but the hallway had 3-plug fifteen feet away.   On the second trip shopped for cords and adapters at Don Quiote, but before securing a solution there were 3 days in Sapporo where a McDonald's had 3-plug outlets in their upstairs dining room. Had to go 2-3 each day to keep charging.  That sucked.  Just be prepared for pluggin' in --- so no time is wasted!  The mornings were great as its coffee time.  So very cold up there.  My previous compliment to McDonald's was based on this Sapporo location.  Food orders ready in less than 60 seconds.   Delicious food from this northern agricultural region.  Anyhow catch you later bro!
